 We denote the total density operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{{\cal W}}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 for the electronic system and the EM field.
 The evolution of total density operator is governed by the quantum Liouville
 equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\widehat{{\cal W}}\left(t\right)=-\frac{i}{\hbar}\left[\widehat{H}_{\text{PZW}},\widehat{{\cal W}}\left(t\right)\right].
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since we want to treat the field degrees of freedom classically, we perform
 the partial Wigner transforms with respect to the vector filed operator,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

, and its conjugate momentum, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{D}}$
\end_inset

.
 Formally, the partial Wigner transform of the density operator gives the
 probability density
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{split}\widehat{\rho}_{W}\left(\mathbf{D},\mathbf{A},t\right)=\frac{1}{\left(2\pi\hbar\right)^{3N}} & \int d\mathbf{Z}e^{i\mathbf{D}\cdot\mathbf{Z}/\hbar}\times\\
 & \left\langle \mathbf{A}-\frac{\mathbf{Z}}{2}\right|\widehat{{\cal W}}\left(t\right)\left|\mathbf{A}+\frac{\mathbf{Z}}{2}\right\rangle ,
\end{split}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the bold symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{D}$
\end_inset

