reference "eq:liouville_rho"

\end_inset

–
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:maxwell_DB"

\end_inset

.
 Suppose that at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

, the initial electronic density matrix is 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\rho}_{0}$
\end_inset

 and the field is represented by an initial distribution in phase space
 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\mathbf{D}_{0},\mathbf{B}_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, we can construct the joint electronic–radiation probability
 density corresponding to a swarm of Ehrenfest trajectories starting from
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{D}_{0},\mathbf{B}_{0},\widehat{\rho}_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The joint probability density for Ehrenfest dynamics is then defined formally
 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{split}\widehat{\rho}_{Eh}\left(\mathbf{D},\mathbf{B},t\right)\equiv & \int\mathrm{d}\mathbf{D}_{0}\int\mathrm{d}\mathbf{B}_{0}f\left(\mathbf{D}_{0},\mathbf{B}_{0}\right)\times\\
 & \widehat{\rho}\left(t;\mathbf{D}_{0},\mathbf{B}_{0},\widehat{\rho}_{0}\right)\times\\
 & \delta\left(\mathbf{D}\left(t;\mathbf{D}_{0},\mathbf{B}_{0},\widehat{\rho}_{0}\right)-\mathbf{D}\right)\times\\
 & \delta\left(\mathbf{B}\left(t;\mathbf{D}_{0},\mathbf{B}_{0},\widehat{\rho}_{0}\right)-\mathbf{B}\right)
\end{split}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\rho}\left(t;\mathbf{D}_{0},\mathbf{B}_{0},\widehat{\rho}_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{D}\left(t;\mathbf{D}_{0},\mathbf{B}_{0},\widehat{\rho}_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}\left(t;\mathbf{D}_{0},\mathbf{B}_{0},\widehat{\rho}_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 are the Ehrenfest trajectory starting from the initial condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{D}_{0},\mathbf{B}_{0},\widehat{\rho}_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 However, there does not exist a formal equation of motion for the joint
 probability density in general.
